    <meta name="description" content="Despite the fact that South America was Europe’s treasure trove for gold and silver from the 1530s through the late 1700s, in the early 21st century the region contributes only a small percentage to the world’s production of these precious metals. Brazil is South America’s leading gold producer, with deposits in the Amazon basin accounting for much of the output. Traditional mining centres in Minas Gerais, Goiás, and Mato Grosso have diminished in importance. Placer deposits in Colombia’s Atrato River basin are significant sources of gold, and the metal is still produced also in Venezuela and in classical gold-mining centres"/>
